","1145":"1145","1266":"1266","1277":"1277","Walton, Leicestershire, England":"Walton, Leicestershire, England","Over Walton Manor, Leicestershire, England":"Walton, Leicestershire, England","Hale, Lancashire, England":"Hale, Lancashire, England","Wellesbourne Hastings, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom":"Wellesbourne Hastings, Warwickshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Ellesmere, Shropshire, England":"Ellesmere, Shropshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Hereford, Herefordshire, England":"Hereford, Herefordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1167–1237":"1167–1237","1180–1260":"1180–1260","1167–1277":"1167–1277","1190–1250":"1190–1250","1197–1266":"1197–1266","1145–1235":"1145–1235","1190":"1190","about 1190":"about 1190","1197":"1197","between 8 January 1189 and 7 January 1190":"from 8 January 1189 to 7 January 1190","1250":"1250","1260":"1260","1180":"1180","1237":"1237","1215":"1215","1235":"1235","1224":"1224","1167":"1167","1145":"1145","1266":"1266","1277":"1277","Walton, Leicestershire, England":"Walton, Leicestershire, England","Over Walton Manor, Leicestershire, England":"Walton, Leicestershire, England","Hale, Lancashire, England":"Hale, Lancashire, England","Wellesbourne Hastings, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom":"Wellesbourne Hastings, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom","Ellesmere, Shropshire, England":"Ellesmere, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","Hereford, Herefordshire, England":"Hereford, Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Walton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of numerous places called Walton, which are named with Old English <i>walh</i> ‘foreigner, Briton, serf’ (genitive plural <i>wala</i>), <i>wald</i> ‘woodland’, <i>wall</i> ‘wall’, or <i>wælla</i> ‘well, spring, stream’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’.","History: George Walton (1741–1804) signed the Declaration of Independence. He was born in Prince Edward County, VA, whither his grandfather had emigrated from England in 1682. He moved to Savannah, GA, and became governor of GA and a prominent jurist."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Herbert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, introduced to Britain by the Normans. It is derived from <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. An Old English form, <i>Herebeorht</i>, existed in England before the Conquest, but was superseded by the Norman form, which gave rise to an important surname. The family in question were earls of Pembroke in the 16th and 17th centuries; they included the poet  George Herbert . By the end of the Middle Ages <i>Herbert</i> was little used, although it remained a favourite with some families, notably the Saint Quintins of East Yorkshire. Its greater frequency in Britain from the 19th century onwards is due partly to the trend for the revival of medieval names of Germanic origin and partly to the trend for the transferred use of surnames."],"variants":[{"name":"Heribert","meanings":["From an Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, introduced to Britain by the Normans. It is derived from <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. An Old English form, <i>Herebeorht</i>, existed in England before the Conquest, but was superseded by the Norman form, which gave rise to an important surname. The family in question were earls of Pembroke in the 16th and 17th centuries; they included the poet  George Herbert . By the end of the Middle Ages <i>Herbert</i> was little used, although it remained a favourite with some families, notably the Saint Quintins of East Yorkshire. Its greater frequency in Britain from the 19th century onwards is due partly to the trend for the revival of medieval names of Germanic origin and partly to the trend for the transferred use of surnames."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":48,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":57,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Herbert de Walton was born in 1167, in Walton, Leicestershire, England as the son of Richard de Meath of Walton. He married Mrs. Margaret De Walton of Hereford from 8 January 1189 to 7 January 1190, in Hereford, Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in 1237, in Ellesmere, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 70."},"et":{"1167–1237":"1167–1237","1180–1260":"1180–1260","1